entry.title: High Surf Advisory issued October 25 at 4:06PM HST until October 26 at 6:00PM HST by NWS Honolulu HI
entry.summary:
...HIGH SURF ADVISORY REMAINS IN EFFECT FOR ALL EAST FACING SHORES THROUGH SATURDAY...
.A moderate to large, medium period NNE (010-030 degrees) swell will produce advisory level surf along east-facing shores through Saturday. The surf is expected to peak this afternoon into the evening, then slowly decline through the weekend.
* WHAT...Large breaking waves of up to 10 to 14 feet through this evening declining to 7 to 10 feet by Saturday afternoon.
* WHERE...Olomana, Maui Windward West, Kauai East, Koolau Windward, Molokai Southeast, Windward Haleakala, Big Island East and Big Island North.
* WHEN...Until 6 PM HST Saturday.
* IMPACTS...Moderate. Strong breaking waves and strong currents will make swimming dangerous.

entry.title: Flash Flood Warning issued October 26 at 11:25AM ChST until October 26 at 3:00PM ChST by NWS Tiyan GU
entry.summary:
FFWGUM
The National Weather Service in Tiyan has extended the
* Flash Flood Warning for... Saipan... Tinian...
* Until 300 PM ChST.
* At 1125 AM ChST, emergency management reported flash flooding across the warned area. Between 2 and 4 inches of rain have fallen. Additional rainfall amounts of 0.5 to 1.5 inches are possible in the warned area. Flash flooding is already occurring.
HAZARD...Flash flooding caused by rain and poor drainage from previous rainfall.
SOURCE...Emergency management reported.
IMPACT...Flash flooding of small creeks and streams, urban areas, and streets as well as other poor drainage and low-lying areas.
* Some locations that will experience flash flooding include... Garapan, Dandan, China Town, Tanapag, As Mahetog, Koblerville, San Jose (Tinian Municipality), Chalan Kanoa I, San Antonio, Chalan Kanoa II, Chalan Kanoa III, San Roque, Kagman, Chalan Kanoa IV, Kagman III, Gualo Rai, Afetnas, Chalan Piao, Fananganan and Chalan Laulau.
Rainfall looks to be decreasing in intensity, but saturated conditions will make it very slow for water to drain away from low-lying areas and certain roads and streets. Continue to practice caution when driving and avoid closed or flooded roads.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued October 25 at 9:22PM EDT by NWS State College PA
entry.summary:
A combination of dry and windy conditions will create an elevated risk of wildfire spread across the southeastern half of PA on Saturday. Relative humidity values dip to the 25 to 40 percent range in the afternoon accompanied by wind gusts out of the northwest between 20 and 30 MPH.
Residents are urged to exercise caution if handling any potential ignition sources, such as machinery, cigarettes, or matches. If dry grasses and tree litter begin to burn, the fire will have the potential to spread rapidly.
For more information about wildfire danger and wildfire prevention and education, please visit the Pennsylvania Department of Conservation and Natural Resources website at http://dcnr.pa.gov/Communities/Wildfire.

entry.title: Flood Warning issued October 25 at 9:20PM EDT by NWS Melbourne FL
entry.summary:
...The Flood Warning continues for the following rivers in Florida...
St Johns River Near Astor affecting Volusia and Lake Counties.
.The Saint Johns River at Astor is forecast to continue a gradual decline through Moderate Flood Stage this weekend into early next week. Residents and interests along the Saint Johns River should be prepared for prolonged flood impacts.
For the St. Johns River...including Astor...Moderate flooding is forecast.
Additional information is available at www.weather.gov.
The next statement will be issued Saturday morning at 1100 AM EDT.
* WHAT...Moderate flooding is occurring and moderate flooding is forecast.
* WHERE...St Johns River near Astor.
* WHEN...Until further notice.
* IMPACTS...At 4.0 feet, Major flooding occurs with water entering many structures on canals and along the river. Long duration flooding will occur, with levels taking weeks to months to return below flood stage. Water rescues will be necessary. River Road becomes inaccessible, with 1 to 2 feet water depth in numerous homes on Wildhog, Possum, Bonnet and Snail roads. Roads along Blue Creek are inaccessible with major flooding of homes on Otter, Branch and Chestnut roads. Camp South Moon Road and Juno Trail are inaccessible.
* ADDITIONAL DETAILS... - At 8:30 PM EDT Friday the stage was 3.9 feet. - Bankfull stage is 2.0 feet. - Recent Activity...The maximum river stage in the 24 hours ending at 8:30 PM EDT Friday was 4.0 feet. - Forecast...The river is expected to rise to a crest of 3.9 feet just after midnight tonight. - Flood stage is 2.3 feet. - http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued October 25 at 5:45PM EDT by NWS Mount Holly NJ
entry.summary:
There continues to be an increased risk of fire spread on Saturday. Relative humidity values Saturday afternoon will drop to 25 to 35 percent across much of the area. These low relative humidity values will combine with northwest winds around 15 mph with gusts up to 25 mph, and even occasionally as high as 30 mph, temperatures in the mid to upper 60s, and abundant sunshine. These conditions will support the spread of any fires that ignite, which could quickly become difficult to control.
Outdoor burning is strongly discouraged. Be sure to properly extinguish or dispose of any potential ignition sources, including smoking materials such as cigarette butts. Refer to your state's forest fire management agency for more information on burn restrictions in your local area.
Relative humidity values will be lower on Sunday, generally ranging from 20 to 30 percent, but winds will be much lighter. Burn restrictions may still be in place given the very dry conditions and lack of any recent rainfall.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued October 25 at 10:57AM AKDT by NWS Juneau AK
entry.summary:
We continue to monitor the possibility of a significant snow event for portions of northern Panhandle beginning Monday night into Tuesday.
Cold air moves into the region this weekend with increasing north winds across the panhandle. Early next week there is high confidence on a low moving into the Gulf of Alaska, spreading moisture and advecting warmer air over the colder airmass.
The main concern regarding this event will be how far east the low is as it moves into the Gulf. A track further east will allow moisture and warmer air to expand farther north, limiting snow amounts. Meanwhile, a track further west will limit how far north the moisture and warming spreads.
The biggest challenge is, when do winds switch from north and east to south and west. This switch would mix warmer air down to the surface allowing for a switch from snow to rain as well as limiting snow accumulations.
As always, the latest forecast information can be found at www.weather.gov/Juneau.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued October 25 at 6:16PM ChST by NWS Tiyan GU
entry.summary:
Tropical Depression Kong-rey (23W) is located west-northwest of Rota near 15N144E and is moving northwest, away from the Marianas. However, radar and satellite data show the heaviest weather is displaced to the north and east of the center, mainly near and north of Tinian and Saipan, with some showers moving into the far northern islands such as Alamagan and Pagan. Strongest winds of 25 to 35 mph and gusts to 60 mph remain in the monsoonal flow wrapping along the eastern and northern edge of TD Kong-rey, and are mainly contained in a band of showers and heavy cloud cover that extends from Tinian up to just north of Anatahan and slopes southeast, east of the Marianas coastal waters, and towards Chuuk, into the overall monsoonal pattern associated with 98W. At Guam and Rota weather as been calmer but rain bands trailing east of TD Kong-rey are moving in this evening and tonight, potentially bringing periods of locally heavy rainfall and gust to 30 mph in these showers.
IMPACTS THROUGH SUNDAY NIGHT:
-For Tinian and Saipan winds will be around 25 to 35 mph. Gust to 60 mph are expected to decrease to 45 mph after midnight tonight as the strongest gusts move northwest and way from the Marianas with TD Kong- rey. For Guam and Rota winds of 15 to 20 mph are expected over night but showers will bring gusts up to 30 mph.
-Greatest potential for heavy rain tonight remain around and north of Tinian and Saipan, extending up to Pagan. Developing rain bands east of Kong-rey will bring periods of locally heavy showers to Guam and Rota over night.
-Winds at Tinian and Saipan are expected to become breezy Saturday morning, dropping to 15 to 25 mph, while 15 to 20 mph are expected for Guam and Rota. Winds across all the Marianas are expected to become 15 to 20 mph Saturday night as the monsoonal pattern start to weaken as TD Kong-rey continues to move away. Scattered to at times numerous showers and isolated thunderstorms will continue through at least Sunday night as the Marianas remains on the edge of the monsoonal pattern and 98W as they are pulled northwest by TD Kong- rey.
-Hazardous surf and marine conditions will start to ease, but surf and sea conditions may remain choppy due to swell from TD Kong-rey and the monsoonal pattern in western Micronesia.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued October 25 at 5:39PM ChST by NWS Tiyan GU
entry.summary:
A strong westerly monsoon pattern persists across western Micronesia. The worst conditions are found between Yap and Chuuk and areas south. Satellite data has shown numerous to widespread showers stretching from just south of Yap Proper eastward into Chuuk State west and northwest of Weno. Strong winds of 20 to 30 mph and rough seas have continued across the region well outside of the showers. Invest 99W has formed into Tropical Depression Kong-rey (23W) while invest 98W is located just southeast of Guam. As both features move northwestward, the monsoonal pattern will lift northwest. This will bring the region of showers and thunderstorms back into Palau and Yap Sunday and into early next week.
This monsoonal pattern will make inter-island travel hazardous and potentially dangerous at times so travel is discouraged through the rest of week and into the weekend. Watch out for high surf along west and north facing reefs and pay attention to surf and sea conditions.
Residents across Yap and Chuuk States should continue to monitor local weather forecasts from the National Weather Service in Guam, and for additional information from your local Weather Service Office and emergency management. Visit weather.gov/gum/PublicForecasts for the latest weather information from the National Weather Service.
